  "success": true,
  "output": "132 configured sources, many paginating 20-40 pages of ~10-20 jobs each — so a single run can push thousands of `Job` objects through the diff/filter path, which is where the real costs concentrate.\n\nOne correction up front: **there's no React/JS anywhere in this repo** (confirmed via `find`/`package.json` check) — this is a pure Python async CLI. I've substituted the equivalent Python concerns (redundant computation, blocking I/O, SQLite query patterns) for the React-specific asks.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55-74)\n\nEvery job does its own `SELECT`, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    elif row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash:\n        changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n```\n\nFor a few thousand jobs/run that's a few thousand round trips through SQLite's parser/planner. Fix: load the whole `{key: content_hash}` map in one query, diff in memory, then batch-write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"]\n                for r in self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\")}\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        (new if h is None else changed if h != job.content_hash else touched).append(job)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(_INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(_UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, j.key) for j in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nThe `jobs` table (key/company/short strings) is trivially small to hold entirely in memory, even at tens of thousands of rows.\n\nRelated: `added_since()` (store.py:127-135) does `WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title` with no index on `first_seen` — full table scan + filesort on every scan. Add:\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job in `filter_jobs` (filters.py:11-41)\n\n`match()` is called once per job, and it calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside** that per-job call — recompiling every include/exclude pattern from scratch for every single job in the run:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call!\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call!\n```\n\nFix — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude): return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include): return False\n    ...\n```\nCompiles N patterns once instead of N×M times (M = jobs fetched, easily thousands).\n\n## 3. Redundant/wasteful computation — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies `raw` just to discard it (models.py:71-75)\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # recursively deep-copies every field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then throws the copy away\n    ...\n```\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively deep-copies nested dicts/lists. `raw` holds the entire unparsed API payload for that job (can be a nontrivial nested dict for Apple/Workday/Meta), and it gets deep-copied on every insert/update just to be discarded a line later. This runs once per job on every `diff()` call.\n\nFix — build the row dict explicitly instead of going through `asdict`:\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\nAlso note `content_hash` is a property recomputed (sha256) on every access — `store.diff()` currently calls `job.content_hash` once for the comparison and `to_row()` computes it again for the write. Not expensive per-call, but easy to avoid by computing once and reusing if you want to squeeze further.\n\n## 4. Redundant computation — double regex scan in Meta fetcher (fetchers.py:894)\n\n```python\ntok = lambda p: (re.search(p, page) or [None, \"\"])[1] if re.search(p, page) else \"\"\n```\nThis runs `re.search(p, page)` **twice** per token lookup, against the full metacareers.com HTML page (hundreds of KB), for 5 different tokens per `fetch_meta()` call. Fix:\n```python\ndef tok(p):\n    m = re.search(p, page)\n    return m[1] if m else \"\"\n```\nHalves the regex scan work in that function for free.\n\n## 5. Caching opportunity — no conditional/incremental fetching\n\nEvery run repaginates entire boards from page 1 (Amazon/Microsoft up to `max_pages=40`, Apple 10, Google 20, Optiver 40, Eightfold 40, Phenom 40) even though most postings haven't changed since the last 12h run. None of the fetchers use `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since` or any last-run cache. Two concrete, low-risk wins:\n- For the \"clean JSON API\" sources sorted newest-first (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Google, Apple — the comments in fetchers.py already note this), you can stop paginating early once you hit a page whose oldest `posted_at` is older than your `max_age_days` filter cutoff, instead of always walking to `max_pages`. Right now `filter_jobs` runs after `fetch_all` fetches everything — pushing the cutoff into the fetch loop for these sources would cut most of the pagination cost.\n- Greenhouse/SmartRecruiters/Recruitee/Workable requests (`_simple`) send no `If-None-Match`; storing the last `ETag` per source in the `meta` table (which already exists) and sending it back would let those boards 304 instead of re-downloading and re-parsing the full JSON every run.\n\n## 6. Blocking I/O — sequential synchronous notifiers (notify.py:102-109)\n\n`pipeline.run()` is `async`, but `dispatch()` fires Slack → webhook → email (SMTP) → SMS **sequentially and synchronously**, each with its own timeout (15s network calls, SMTP handshake). If more than one channel is configured, their latencies stack instead of overlapping. Not a correctness bug, but if you ever add more channels or a slow SMTP host, this is where run time balloons. Since you're already in an `asyncio` context, converting these to `httpx.AsyncClient` calls run via `asyncio.gather` (keeping `notify_console` synchronous, since it's just prints) would let them run concurrently.\n\n## Memory leaks — none found, and here's why to not worry about it\n\nThis is a short-lived batch process (invoked fresh per scheduled run, per the 12h-cron commit), not a long-running server — so the usual \"unbounded growth in a persistent process\" leak class doesn't apply. Worth confirming: `fetch_all()` (fetchers.py:1126-1147) correctly closes its own `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `finally` block even on exceptions, and `Store` is used as a context manager that closes the sqlite connection. No dangling connections or unclosed clients found.\n\n## Priority ranking\n\n1. **`Store.diff()` batching** (#1) — biggest win, straightforward, safe refactor, touches every run.\n2. **Regex recompilation in `filter_jobs`** (#2) — trivial fix, scales with job volume.\n3. **`to_row()` deep-copy** (#3) — easy fix, removes wasted allocation on every write.\n4. **Early-stop pagination on sorted sources** (#5) — more involved (touches per-fetcher logic) but cuts real network+parse time, which dominates wall-clock versus the SQLite/regex work above.\n5. **Meta double-scan** (#4) and **async notifiers** (#6) — minor, do opportunistically.\n",
